1 Lesson 3: mutating joins 1

1.1 Learning objectives

  1. Mutating joins functions in practice
  2. pitfalls when joining data

Mutating joins are the crucial functions that you need to know when working with data relations. There are 4 main functions:

  • left_join()

  • right_join()

  • inner_join()

  • full_join()

These 4 functions share the same syntax and are considered one of the pillars of data science. Indeed, joining functions, are present in other programming languages like Python and SQL and even if the syntax might look different, the concepts are the same.

library(here)
library(dplyr)
library(readr)

Differently from binding functions (bind_rows() & bind_cols), the mutating join functions come in handy when we need to join together dataframes with different columns.

1.1.1 left_join()

The concept of left_join() is that everything on the left dataframe is retained and joins every row that matches base on criteria from the right table. Here below you can see a visual representation of the concept.

Source: PsyTeachR

letâs try to use this new function. For this task, we are gonna use the YaoundÃ© dataframe. First, we filter and select only some variables and rows from the original dataframe to ease the task.

yaounde <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/yaounde_covid_seroprev_dataset.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

yaounde_1 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "n_hhld_rooms", "n_hhld_adults", "n_hhld_children") %>%
  slice(2:25)

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "loc_hhld_area", "loc_hhld_lat", "loc_hhld_long") %>%
  slice(2:20)

The yaounde_1 dataframe columns refer to the number of rooms (n_hhld_rooms), adults (n_hhld_adults) and children (n_hhld_children) in a specific household, while yaounde_2 reports some geographical information about the household location i.e.Â name of the area (loc_hhld_area), latitude (loc_hhld_lat ) and longitude (loc_hhld_long). Both dataframes contain a unique index (id_quest) that is the criteria that we can use to join our data i.e.Â every row on the right dataframe will be matched with a row on the left dataframe whenever the id_quest is the same. Letâs try

yaounde_lj <-
  left_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_lj
## # A tibble: 24 x 7

## #   loc_hhld_long <dbl>

If you try to explore the resulting dataframe you will notice that yaounde_1 and yaounde_2 are joined together based on the id_quest. As mentioned above, left_join() keeps everything from the left dataframe, even when the dataframes have different lengths as in our case. When there are no matches with the right dataframe, the missing values are simply replaced with NA. Here you can appreciate the advantages compared to bind_rows() function.

If you desire you can also use more criteria to join dataframes e.g.Â you can write the above code as follow combining the criteria into a vector with c()

#yaounde_lj <-
  #left_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = c("id_quest", "criteria_2", "criteria_3"))

When you are using multiple criteria you have to be careful and be sure that at least one of your variables can identify in a unique way your rows. The risk to consider when using left_join(), is that your variables might join data in a wrong way

Letâs illustrate one last scenario i.e.Â when the right dataframe contains more matches with the left dataframe. Here below we modify yaounde_2 by duplicating each row

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde_2 %>% 
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 2))

letâs the the left_join()

yaounde_lj_duplicates <-
  left_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_lj_duplicates
## # A tibble: 43 x 7
##    id_quest             n_hhld_rooms n_hhld_adults n_hhld_children loc_hhld_area
##    <chr>                       <dbl>         <dbl>           <dbl> <chr>        
##  1 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere     
##  2 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere     
##  3 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere     
##  4 CARRIERE/NUM/002/00~            2             3               1 carriere     
##  5 CARRIERE/NUM/038/00~            5             2               4 carriere     
##  6 CARRIERE/NUM/038/00~            5             2               4 carriere     
##  7 CARRIERE/NUM/038/00~            5             2               4 carriere     
##  8 CARRIERE/NUM/038/00~            5             2               4 carriere     
##  9 CARRIERE/NUM/015/00~            4             6               1 carriere     
## 10 CARRIERE/NUM/015/00~            4             6               1 carriere     
## # ... with 33 more rows, and 2 more variables: loc_hhld_lat <dbl>,
## #   loc_hhld_long <dbl>

What we obtained is a dataframe of dimension 43 x 7. Why this? As we mentioned every row from the right dataframe is matched with the rows of the left dataframe based on a matching criteria. The right dataframe (yaounde_2) has 38 rows, where each row is duplicated (i.e.Â 19 unique id_quest). The left dataframe (yaounde_1) has no duplicates and consist of 24 unique rows where 19 of those have 2 matching with the right dataframe. If you do the math, you will see that the matching are 19 * 2 (because of duplicate2 in yaounde_2 ) which is equal to 38, and then you have to add the 5 rows that are present only in the left dataframe. The final result is 43, which is the length of yaounde_lj_duplicates.

Again, keep in mind that is a good practice to explore the data and have in mind the size of the expected outcome when using mutating joins functions.

Before moving to the other functions there is still one case to consider when using the left_join() function which is the case where the 2 dataframes have more columns in common that are not used inside the argument by. Letâs modify our yaounde_1 and yaounde_2

yaounde_1 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "n_hhld_rooms", "n_hhld_adults", "n_hhld_children", "loc_hhld_area") %>%
  slice(2:25)

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "loc_hhld_area", "loc_hhld_lat", "loc_hhld_long") %>%
  slice(2:20)

Here we simply added the variable âloc_hhld_areaâ to yaounde_1

yaounde_lj <-
  left_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

yaounde_lj

When looking at the outcome you can see that both âloc_hhld_areaâ are retained but are also renamed with .x and .y in the name end. In this way, left_join() helps you to know that the 2 columns come from different dataframes. Indeed, in our example the 2 columns are actually identical, but when dealing with real data it can frequently happen that your dataframes have the same columns name but the values are different. If you like, you can personalize the way the variables are renamed with the attribute suffix

yaounde_lj <-
  left_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2,
            by = c("id_quest"),
            suffix = c("_yaounde_1", "_yaounde_2"))

yaounde_lj

1.1.2 right_join()

We wonât spend much time on this function because its functioning is the same as left_join(), the only difference is that it retains all the elements from the right dataframe matching those from the left

Source: PsyTeachR

letâs check an example with the same data we used so far

yaounde_1 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "n_hhld_rooms", "n_hhld_adults", "n_hhld_children") %>%
  slice(2:25)

yaounde_2 <- 
  yaounde %>%
  select("id_quest", "loc_hhld_area", "loc_hhld_lat", "loc_hhld_long") %>%
  slice(2:20)
yaounde_rj <-
  right_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")

As you can see, now the join is made on the right.

One important thing to know is that whether you decide to use left_join() or right_join() does not really matter but what is crucial is the position of the dataframes inside the function based on the function you choose. Letâs test an example to clarify the concept

The following 2 chunks of code provide the same result

yaounde_test_rj <-
  right_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")
yaounde_lj <-
  left_join(yaounde_2, yaounde_1, by = "id_quest")

The only difference would be the order of the columns. Differently, doing the following

yaounde_test_rj <-
  right_join(yaounde_1, yaounde_2, by = "id_quest")
yaounde_test_rj <-
  right_join(yaounde_2, yaounde_1, by = "id_quest")

Will lead to different result
